{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473610"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:11:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:11:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2575"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2575"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.05,0.08,0.03,0.83]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2575"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78959"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2575"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2575"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64308"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"645"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2702"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2718"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27078"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78959"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department by his parent after the child was seen swallowing a battery. One hour ago, the parent was changing glucometer batteries when they witnessed the boy taking a battery and swallowing it. The child does not have any symptoms. He is alert and conscious. His vital signs are unremarkable. A chest X-ray shows a radiopaque circular object with a halo sign in the distal oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in the management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Elective endoscopic removal","Induction of emesis","Observation","Serial X-rays","Urgent endoscopic removal"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EForeign body ingestion is a common occurrence in children due to increased oral exploratory behaviour. This patient was witnessed swallowing a battery. Patients who have high-risk features need to undergo \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent endoscopic removal\u003C/strong\u003E of the foreign body. The high-risk features are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA sharp object (e.g., needle, fishbone) located in the oesophagus, stomach, or proximal duodenum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBattery located in the oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo or more magnets located in the oesophagus or stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESymptomatic patients (e.g., drooling, respiratory compromise).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESince this patient has a high-risk feature (i.e., battery located in the oesophagus), he needs to undergo urgent endoscopic removal. This is almost certainly a button battery. Impaction of these types of battery in the oesophagus can lead to necrosis and perforation of the oesophagus within two hours. Even if the patient is asymptomatic, he should undergo endoscopic removal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElective endoscopic removal\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this scenario as the urgency of the situation requires immediate action to prevent tissue damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInduction of emesis\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as it can lead to oesophageal perforation if the foreign body is severely impacted in the oesophagus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eserial X-rays\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated in ordinary battery ingestion if the battery is located distal to the gastro-oesophageal sphincter (e.g., within the stomach or intestines) and the patient is asymptomatic. Observation and serial X-rays may also be indicated in patients who do not have high-risk features (e.g., ingestion of a coin and asymptomatic).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Any suspicion of a swallowed button battery needs active intervention.","Button batteries in the oesophagus can cause rapid tissue damage and require urgent removal."],"references":["Button battery ingestion [published 2020 Aug]. In: eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2021 Mar. \u003Chttps://www.tg.org.au\u003E","R\u00edos G, Rodr\u00edguez L, Lucero Y, Miquel I, Arancibia ME, Alliende F. Endoscopic Findings Associated With Button Battery Ingestion in Children: Do We Need to Change the Protocol for Managing Gastric Location? Pediatr Emerg Care. 2020 Nov;36(11):523-526. doi: 10.1097/PEC.0000000000001415. PMID: 29369264. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29369264/","Khalaf RT, Ruan W, Orkin S, Wilsey M, Fishman DS, Mallon D, Pan Z, Hazleton KZ, Kramer RE, Walker T. Gastric injury secondary to button battery ingestions: a retrospective multicenter review. Gastrointest Endosc. 2020 Aug;92(2):276-283. doi: 10.1016/j.gie.2020.04.037. Epub 2020 Apr 22. PMID: 32334020; PMCID: PMC7422336. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32334020/","Bulna A, Fifi AC. Endoscopic Evaluation for Stricture Formation Post Button Battery Ingestion. Pediatr Rep. 2021 Sep 1;13(3):511-519. doi: 10.3390/pediatric13030059. PMID: 34564342; PMCID: PMC8482093. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34564342/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64308"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2575"}},"